{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600779"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:07:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:07:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15634"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15634"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71017"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8325"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15634"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56487"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7010"},{"type":"tags","id":"7178"},{"type":"tags","id":"9878"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20092"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71017"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to her GP with episodes of headaches, palpitations and profuse sweating that occur several times per week. Her blood pressure is 180/100 mmHg. Further investigation reveals a 3 cm mass in her right adrenal gland.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological origin of the cells causing this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Post-ganglionic sympathetic neurons","Pre-ganglionic sympathetic neurons","Post-ganglionic parasympathetic neurons","Pre-ganglionic parasympathetic neurons","Adrenal cortical cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with a phaeochromocytoma, a tumour arising from the adrenal medulla. The adrenal medulla functions as modified \u003Cstrong\u003Epost-ganglionic sympathetic neurons\u003C/strong\u003E, which develop from neural crest cells during embryological development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPre-ganglionic sympathetic neurons\u003C/strong\u003E originate from the spinal cord, not neural crest cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-ganglionic parasympathetic neurons\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Epre-ganglionic parasympathetic neurons\u003C/strong\u003E are part of the parasympathetic nervous system and do not give rise to the adrenal medulla\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal cortical cells\u003C/strong\u003E develop from mesoderm, not neural crest cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the embryological origin helps explain why phaeochromocytomas secrete excess catecholamines, producing symptoms of sympathetic overactivity including hypertension, tachycardia, and sweating.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The adrenal medulla is embryologically derived from neural crest cells and functions as a modified post-ganglionic sympathetic neuron.","Phaeochromocytomas are tumours of the adrenal medulla that secrete excess catecholamines.","Classic symptoms of phaeochromocytoma include episodic headaches, sweating, and tachycardia due to catecholamine excess."],"references":["Lotfi CFP, Kremer JL, Dos Santos Passaia B, Cavalcante IP. The human adrenal cortex: growth control and disorders. Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2018 Sep 6;73(suppl 1):e473s. doi: 10.6061/clinics/2018/e473s. PMID: 30208164; PMCID: PMC6113920","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA","Allen MJ, Sharma S. Physiology, Adrenocorticotropic Hormone (ACTH) [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK500031/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56487"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15634"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56487"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T18:50:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T18:50:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8325"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71017"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"descriptio